# RedirectHttpResult does not emit 302 OpenAPI response metadata for Minimal APIs

### Describe the bug

For a Minimal API endpoint returning `Results<RedirectHttpResult, NotFound>`, the generated OpenAPI document does not include a `302` response for `TypedResults.Redirect(...)`.

XML documentation comments are being applied to other response codes on the same endpoint. In the repro below, the `<response code="404">` comment is emitted, but `<response code="302">` is not emitted unless `Produces(StatusCodes.Status302Found)` is added manually.

This issue and repro were generated with assistance from Codex.

### Expected Behavior

The OpenAPI document for the endpoint returning `RedirectHttpResult` should include a `302` response, or XML `<response code="302">` should create that response entry the same way the `404` XML response is applied.

### Actual Behavior

The implicit redirect endpoint only contains `404` in the generated OpenAPI responses. Adding `.Produces(StatusCodes.Status302Found)` manually produces the expected `302` response.

### Repro

Using .NET SDK `11.0.100-preview.4.26230.115`.

Create `openapi-redirect-repro.cs`:

```csharp
#!/usr/bin/env dotnet
#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web
#:package Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@11.0.0-preview.4.26230.115
#:property ManagePackageVersionsCentrally=false
#:property GenerateDocumentationFile=true
#:property PublishAot=false

using System.Text.Json;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.HttpResults;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapOpenApi();

app.MapGet("/implicit/{code}", ReproHandlers.RedirectImplicit);

app.MapGet("/explicit/{code}", ReproHandlers.RedirectExplicit)
    .Produces(StatusCodes.Status302Found);

await app.StartAsync();

try {
    var openApiUrl = $"{app.Urls.Single()}/openapi/v1.json";
    using var client = new HttpClient();
    using var document = JsonDocument.Parse(await client.GetStringAsync(openApiUrl));

    PrintResponses(document, "/implicit/{code}");
    PrintResponses(document, "/explicit/{code}");
} finally {
    await app.StopAsync();
}

static void PrintResponses(JsonDocument document, string path) {
    var responses = document.RootElement
        .GetProperty("paths")
        .GetProperty(path)
        .GetProperty("get")
        .GetProperty("responses");

    Console.WriteLine($"{path} responses:");

    foreach (var response in responses.EnumerateObject()) {
        var description = response.Value.GetProperty("description").GetString();
        Console.WriteLine($"  {response.Name}: {description}");
    }
}

static class ReproHandlers {
    /// <summary>
    /// Redirects to the original URL without explicit Produces metadata.
    /// </summary>
    /// <response code="302">Redirects to the original URL.</response>
    /// <response code="404">If the short link is not found.</response>
    public static Results<RedirectHttpResult, NotFound> RedirectImplicit(string code) {
        return code == "exists"
            ? TypedResults.Redirect("https://example.com")
            : TypedResults.NotFound();
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Redirects to the original URL with explicit Produces metadata.
    /// </summary>
    /// <response code="302">Redirects to the original URL.</response>
    /// <response code="404">If the short link is not found.</response>
    public static Results<RedirectHttpResult, NotFound> RedirectExplicit(string code) {
        return code == "exists"
            ? TypedResults.Redirect("https://example.com")
            : TypedResults.NotFound();
    }
}
```

Run:

```bash
dotnet openapi-redirect-repro.cs
```

Output:

```text
/implicit/{code} responses:
  404: If the short link is not found.
/explicit/{code} responses:
  404: If the short link is not found.
  302: Redirects to the original URL.
```

### Environment

- .NET SDK: `11.0.100-preview.4.26230.115`
- Package: `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi@11.0.0-preview.4.26230.115`
- OS: Windows

### Notes

`RedirectHttpResult` appears not to contribute response metadata automatically, unlike result types such as `Ok` and `NotFound` that emit `ProducesResponseTypeMetadata`. The explicit `Produces(StatusCodes.Status302Found)` workaround functions as expected.

Add blob() method to DotNetStreamReference

## Description

This PR implements the `blob()` method for `DotNetStreamReference` as requested in issue #61826.

### Changes Made:
- Add async `blob(mimeType?: string): Promise<Blob>` method to `DotNetStream` class in `Microsoft.JSInterop.ts`
- Update JavaScript interop tests in `jsinteroptests.js` to validate blob functionality
- Method allows optional MIME type parameter for content-type headers
- Follows the same pattern as existing `arrayBuffer()` method

### Usage Example:
```javascript
// Get stream data as a Blob
const blob = await dotNetStreamRef.blob('application/pdf');

// Create download link
const url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
const a = document.createElement('a');
a.href = url;
a.download = 'document.pdf';
a.click();

// Display image
const img = document.createElement('img');
img.src = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
```

